                  <persName id="t18300114-107-person777">
                  LYDIA 
                  WATKINS
               <interp inst="t18300114-107-person777" type="surname" value="WATKINS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300114-107-person777" type="given" value="LYDIA"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300114-107-person777" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the wife of George Watkins - he <rs id="t18300114-107-viclabel584" type="occupation">keeps a printing-office and circulating library</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300114-107-victim776 t18300114-107-viclabel584"></join>, in Chapel-row, Ball's-pond. On the 2nd of December the prisoner and another came to my house, after eight o'clock in the evening - my husband and I were sitting in the parlour - I saw a reflection between the door and the gas-light; I got up, and saw the prisoner and another lad in the shop;<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183001140058"></xptr>I went in, and they said they wanted to purchase a small book - I said I had not got it, but found I had; the prisoner then asked if I would buy some pin-cushions he had to sell - I said No, and they went away; soon afterwards I missed a pocket-book and a pack of cards from the window - my husband gave an alarm, and they were taken; this property was found on the prisoner.</p>
               <p>JOHN SKIDMORE. I took the prisoner and the other lad; four packs of cards and a pocket-book were found on the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300114-107-person778">
                  WILLIAM 
                  MORTON
               <interp inst="t18300114-107-person778" type="surname" value="MORTON"></interp>
